<p><b>Who wrote the script for Fences?</b> Fences is a 2016 American period drama film directed and co-produced by Denzel Washington from a screenplay by August Wilson, based on his 1985 play of the same name.</p>
<p><b>What is the main point of Fences by August Wilson?</b> The purpose of Fences by August Wilson is to explore the Black family experience and how it changes through subsequent generations.</p>
<p><b>When was August Wilson's Fences written?</b> August Wilson began writing Fences (US/UK) in 1982, immediately following his work on the development of Ma Rainey's Black Bottom (US/UK) at the Eugene O'Neill Playwrights Conference.</p>
<p><b>What is the language and style of Fences by August Wilson?</b> The characters in Fences by August Wilson use a variety of language styles that reflect their backgrounds, education, and time period. The playwright uses a mix of standard English and African-American vernacular to capture the way different characters speak.</p>
<p><b>What is the main summary of Fences?</b> August Wilson's "Fences" is about a man and his family in Pittsburgh, PA in the 1950s-1960s. The family faces hardships related to race relations, opportunity, betrayal, relationships, etc.</p>
<p><b>What is the story behind Fences?</b> A working-class African-American father tries to raise his family in the 1950s, while coming to terms with the events of his life.</p>
<p><b>Why is the play called Fences?</b> The title of the play maps the contours of a conflicted world whose inhabitants strive both for security and release. Literally, Troy Maxson is building a fence around his property; fences protect and enclose, but also shut out.</p>
<p><b>Who is the hero in Fences?</b> Troy Maxson The protagonist of Fences, a fifty-three year-old Black man who works for the sanitation department, lifting garbage into trucks. Troy is also a former baseball star in the Negro Leagues.</p>
<p><b>What are the symbols in Fences?</b> To Rose, a fence is a symbol of her love and her desire for a fence indicates that Rose represents love and nurturing. Troy and Cory on the other hand think the fence is a drag and reluctantly work on finishing Rose's project. Bono also observes that to some people, fences keep people out and push people away.</p>
<p><b>What is the author's purpose in Fences?</b> In Fences as in Wilson's other plays, a tragic character helps pave the way for other Black Americans to have opportunities under conditions they were never free to experience, but never reap from their own sacrifice and talents themselves.</p>
<p><b>What type of drama is Fences?</b> Fences is a 1985 play by the American playwright August Wilson. Set in the 1950s, it is the sixth in Wilson's ten-part "Pittsburgh Cycle". Like all of the "Pittsburgh" plays, Fences explores the evolving African-American experience and examines race relations, among other themes.</p>
<p><b>What was August Wilson's writing style?</b> Answer and Explanation: His style is realistic and authentic, featuring profound emotions and insights presented in the language of everyday people.</p>
<p><b>What are the four theme of Fences?</b> The main themes in Fences are race, barriers, and responsibility and love. Race: Racism has had a profound effect on Troy's life, and it is his fear that racism will prevent Cory from achieving success that leads to Troy irreparably damaging his relationship with his son.</p>
<p><b>What is the theme of the poem Fences?</b> The poem shows how class privilege creates a restrictive and unequal society, barring the less fortunate from their own local resources while granting the rich access to virtually anything. The poem begins by contrasting tourists' experience of a coastal paradise with that of the speaker's family.</p>
<p><b>What is the motif in Fences?</b> Characters in Fences literally and figuratively employ the motif of seeds, flowers, plants, and related actions like growing, taking root, planting, and gestationâ€”in both their language and actions. Like August Wilson's mother whose name is Daisy, Rose has the name of a flower.</p>
<p><b>Who wrote the poem Fences?</b> In this poem, Pat Mora, who grew up in a Spanish speaking home in El Paso, Texas, contrasts the lives of rich tourists with the less fortunate people who serve them.</p>
<p><b>Who is telling the story in Fences?</b> Troy turns the time when he was sick with pneumonia in Mercy Hospital into a fanciful story about his fight with a character named Death. Even as Rose provides the real story to Bono, Troy continues telling his tale.</p>
<p><b>Who wrote the Pulitzer Prize winning play Fences?</b> Fences, by August Wilson - The Pulitzer Prizes. For a distinguished play by an American author, preferably original in its source and dealing with American life, One thousand dollars ($1,000).</p>
<p><b>Why did the author write Fences?</b> Quick answer: Wilson's motivation to write Fences was to articulate the condition of African- Americans in the early stages of integrated society and to depict the reality of how African- Americans navigate social constructs.</p>